<p>
  There's a moment every AI team hits. You've deployed your agents. They're handling real users. And something feels off. Response quality is drifting. Users are complaining about tone. Your metrics show rising ticket escalations but you can't <em>see</em> what changed.
</p>

<p>
  You're flying blind. And that's the problem.
</p>

<p>
  Every other complex system has visualization. Your infrastructure has Grafana. Your database has query plans. Your network has topology maps. But your AI agents — the most unpredictable systems you've ever deployed — get a chat log and a prayer.
</p>

<p>
  We built NeuralSpace to fix this.
</p>

<h2>The idea</h2>

<p>
  NeuralSpace is a real-time 3D visualization of your agent's behavioral state. Not a metaphor. Not a dashboard with brain clip art. A literal, interactive, WebGL-rendered brain where each region maps to a measurable behavioral function — and lights up when that function activates during a live session.
</p>

<p>
  When your support agent starts over-apologizing, you can <strong>see</strong> Broca's Area flare orange. When it hedges every answer with "I think maybe perhaps," you watch the Prefrontal Cortex pulse with indecision. When sycophancy kicks in and it agrees with contradictory user statements, the Parietal Lobe — context integration — goes dark.
</p>

<p>
  It sounds like science fiction. It's not. It's running in production right now, inside the holomime Enterprise dashboard.
</p>

